I think the changed assert just works around the problem: _Swing requires all interaction with components to be done on the EDT_. This requirement is obviously violated (the implementation in `SwingUtilities.java` in the JDK looks sane).

But looking at the stack trace the problem seems to be in the `ActionInvoker`. This is the code:

```java
    private static void doPerformAction(Action action, final ActionInvoker.ActionRunnable r) {
        assert java.awt.EventQueue.isDispatchThread() : "Action " + action.getClass().getName() +
        " may not be invoked from the thread " + Thread.currentThread().getName() +
        ", only the event queue: http://www.netbeans.org/download/4_1/javadoc/OpenAPIs/apichanges.html#actions-event-thread";

        if (r.async && !r.needsToBeSynchronous()) {
            Runnable r2 = new Runnable() {
                    public void run() {
                        r.doRun();
                    }
                };

            RP.post(r2);
        } else {
            r.run();
        }
    }
```

The stack trace shows, that the first branch is taken, so this is a threading violation and modifying the assert just plasters over that fact. Netbeans has several places, that have similar problems and an easy way to find them is to run with substance LAF.

IMHO: The assert needs to stay as it was. For the end user builds this is a non-problem, as the production builds have assertions disabled. The real fix would be to move Swing interaction into the EDT.

